metadata.name: ylb-mess-A #378
metadata.description:
With colors and shapes reminiscent of childhood LEGO explorations, 'ylb-mess-A' explores the assembly process in reverse, using recursive subdivision to create detailed structures instead of progressively building a complex structure brick by brick. Although the tools I use to explore and create have changed over the years, this piece reminds me of the natural creative curiosity that was instilled in me at an early age, for which I am incredibly grateful.

metadata.name: Puzzles of the mind #23
metadata.description:
This is abstract art based on mathematical structure.
The puzzle of your mind seems broken and rearranged.

Mode has 2 variations.
 - Normal
 - Black
Color has 3 variations.
 - 常磐-tokiwa- (Green)
 - 真朱-shinshu- (Red)
 - 紺碧-konpeki- (Blue)
Color Level has 2 variations.
 - High
 - Low
Square Size has 3 variations.
 - Small
 - Middle
 - Large

Tokiwa is a Japanese word meaning always the same. It's green like the color of evergreen leaves.

Shinshu is a Japanese word that refers to a dull red color like vermilion. It means vermilion in its natural state with nothing mixed in.

Konpeki is a Japanese word that describes a deep blue, very close to azure. It's like a clear sky with summer sunshine.

Controls (in live view):
 - Press [f] to switch full screen on and off
 - Press [s] to download a PNG file with windowsize
 - Press [l] to download a PNG file with large size 4800 pixel (wait a minutes)

Create with p5.js
License: CC BY-NC-SA 4.0

metadata.name: The Climb #110
metadata.description:
The climb is about the search for purpose.

Everyone needs a purpose, a path that leads somewhere. Whether you reach it or not is not the point, it’s about the climb. The search for a purpose gives our life meaning. It gives us a reason to look for something more.

Unfortunately, there is no universal truth as to what your purpose in life is. Everyone is unique. Different. We are the product of our upbringing, environment and the cumulative sum of thousands of microdecisions. We need to find meaning for ourselves. Our unique meaning. On this path, we climb alone.

“The Climb” is created to be raw, unique, beautiful and violently volatile, much like our lives.


Everything is written in javascript and p5js.
It can sometimes take a little while to render on older computers.

metadata.name: Garden Of Symmetry #339
metadata.description:
Sometimes, things look better when seen from the distance. Not from far away, but from a length that allows one to see what’s possibly underneath. Or, you may not see anything. Instead, you can just enjoy things falling into place.

Get a pack of shattered glass, snow, or ice*, uncovering a pattern. Or an axis of dancing geometries. Enter the Garden of Symmetry.

The graphic is a plottable SVG file in A3 format, ready to be drawn using a pen plotter. In the full screen view, click somewhere on the artwork to download a copy.

I recommend to optimize the SVG before plotting, i.e. using vpype. I also recommend to draw the graphic using 0.7mm pen.

License: CC BY-SA 4.0 https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/4.0/ - @jakub_antolak

metadata.name: Blueprints of balance #24
metadata.description:
Balance in art is one of the basic principles of design, along with contrast, movement, rhythm, emphasis, pattern, unity, and variety. Balance refers to how the elements of art (line, shape, color, value, space, form, texture) relate to each other within the composition in terms of their visual weight to create visual equilibrium. That is, one side does not seem heavier than another.

But there is no balance without Chaos. And that is why for one hour everyday each Blueprint of balance let it go and turns into its alternative wild version.

metadata.name: forest #70
metadata.description: a color rhapsody

This project is inspired by contemporary artist Ding Yi's work "Appearance of the Cross". It represents my effort in achieving the balance of retaining Ding Yi's maximalism aesthetics while providing a potential to see patterns in there.  

The 8 color palettes are inspired by Ding Yi and risograph colors as well. There are 3 different ways of how colors are chosen, and a small chance the X is drawn with two colors.  

The marks are drawn onto a large 3600x3600px canvas and shown as a resized preview in 800x800px. You can press 's' to save the original sized canvas in PNG which can be printed up to 20x20in at 180dpi.  

Made with p5js.

metadata.name: Murals #151
metadata.description:
'Murals' is a collection of 256 abstract compositions born out of an intense period diving deeply into street art, pointillism and the inner workings of neural networks.

The work explores projection, refraction and abstraction of points as they ripple through multi-dimensional space-time. Points refract through multi-dimensional space to become shapes, which then become coordinate systems for the projections of new points that create a sense of form, texture, lighting, and material properties. 

The work is also a celebration of imperfections and how a combination of many tiny – almost individually imperceptibly small – imperfect details can shape our perceptions of form, materiality, mood. This is explored within this work through subtle uses of sprays, flecks, scuffs, cuts, grain, targets (projections of projections), construction lines, base projections, occasional glitches that cause curvature, bounced light, shadows, and more.

Features:

15 colour palettes: 
Scream, Night Bus, Double Backflip, Jaws, Sunday, Atom, Space, Tipex, 
Graphite, Leaf, Earth, Bubble Gum, Citrus, Jellyfish, Damp Concrete.

4 times of day (that create subtle changes in light colour):
Daylight, Winter Morning, Midnight, Sunset

2 Border types: 
Normal, Thin

Various features that subtly impact appearance surface textures and shard forms:
Metallic, Engrave, Number of Shards, Scuff Marks, Symmetry. 

Controls:
- Press [ S ] to save the work at its current image size as a PNG.
- Press [ 1 ] to set the image size to 1440 x 1944 pixels (default size)
- Press [ 2 ] to set the image size to 2880 x 3888 pixels
- Press [ 3 ] to set the image size to 4320 x 5832 pixels

- Press [ F ] to toggle freeform mode to create custom image sizes and aspect ratios
- Press [ R ] to reload the image (for use in freeform mode)

This work has been tested on Chrome and Safari on Mac OS, and also using an Android smartphone. Please make sure that it works on your device before minting. Based on testing (in May 2022), each work should take about 5-10 seconds to fully load on a laptop or desktop machine, and 15-20 seconds on a mobile device. The loading process is animated so you can watch the construction the static artwork during this time. 

This artwork is created with p5.js 

@nbswwit, 2022

metadata.name: Glomularus #84
metadata.description:
Glomularus is an exploration in generative, artificial life forms. The project is an extension of my Protobyte series, begun in 2004.

Driven by Verlet icosahedra and responsive tendrils, Glomulari live in a spherical virtual ecosystem (V-eco) enhanced through user interaction.

Interaction:

Mouse/Trackpad:
  drag -> camera rotation
  drag + CMD/CTR -> camera pan
  scroll wheel/pinch -> camera zoom

Key Input:
  1-9: add acceleration
  -, +: reduce | increase V-eco sphere radius
  f, g: reduce | increase fog
  p: screen capture

Tip:
To decrease creature acceleration, reduce V-eco sphere radius

Note:
Please post your favorite Glomularus screen captures
TW: @iragreenberg
IG: @greenberg.ira

Built with Three.js, PByte.js, TypeScript, Node

metadata.name: Uglyy[GEN](0) #22
metadata.description:
Uglyy[GEN](0) 

Genesis Generative Artwork coded entirely in p5.js.

An interpretation of the legendary BASIC program for the Commodore 64:

10 PRINT CHR$(205.5+RND(1)); : GOTO 10

A study of basic p5.js coding, animation, and color theory.
